			<span class="kicker"><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/category/main-topics/investment-banking/">Investment Banking</a> | <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/category/main-topics/legal/">Legal/Regulatory</a></span>		</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">For Spanish Lenders, What a Difference Two Years Make</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Raphael Minder			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-10-27T16:32:56+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">October 27, 2014 12:32 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">October 27, 2014 12:32 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/10/27/spanish-lenders-ecb-stress-tests/" data-title="For Spanish Lenders, What a Difference Two Years Make" data-description="Spanish officials welcomed the results of European stress tests, which indicated that the country&#039;s banking sector had returned to good health after it was close to collapse in 2012. ">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/28/business/dbpix-eubanks-spain/dbpix-eubanks-spain-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/28/business/dbpix-eubanks-spain/dbpix-eubanks-spain-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/28/business/dbpix-eubanks-spain/dbpix-eubanks-spain-blog480.jpg" id="100000003199616" width="480" height="326" alt="Protestors at the headquarters of Liberbank in Oviedo, Spain, in 2013."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="326"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Protestors at the headquarters of Liberbank in Oviedo, Spain, in 2013.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Eloy Alonso/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div class="entry entry-related">
<h4>Related Links</h4>
<div class="entry-related">
<ul>
<li><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/10/26/ecb-stress-test-finds-13-banks-fall-short/">Just 13 Eurozone Banks Fail Test, in Possible Economic Turning Point</a></li>
</ul></div>
</p></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">BARCELONA â How did they do it?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Two years ago, Spanish banks were in crisis, in such bad shape that they put the eurozone at risk and required a lifeline of 41 billion euros, or $52 billion, to stay afloat.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Now, the slimmed-down Spanish banking sector, bolstered by significant provisions against bad mortgage loans and fresh capital injections from private investors, can take comfort in the results of <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/10/26/ecb-stress-test-finds-13-banks-fall-short/">stress tests</a> by the <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/e/european_central_bank/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about European Central Bank">European Central Bank</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Of the 15 Spanish banks examined by the central bank, only one â the small lender Liberbank â was shown to have a capital deficit at the end of 2013, according to results released by the central bank on Sunday. At the end of last year,Â Liberbank had a deficit of â¬32.2 million, but since then it has taken steps to bolster its finances, including a capital increase in June that was fully subscribed by investors and yielded â¬475 million of fresh money.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Spanish officials welcomed the results of the <a href="https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/1346518-european-bank-stress-test-results.html">European Central Bank review</a>, which they said demonstrated that the country&#8217;s banking sector had bounced back since it was close to collapse in 2012. At that time, Bankia, a giant mortgage lender, reported the largest loss in Spanish banking history and forced Spain to negotiate <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2012/06/10/business/global/spain-moves-closer-to-bailout-of-banks.html">a banking bailout</a> with its <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/e/european_union/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about the European Union.">European Union</a> partners.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the end, Spain required â¬41 billion of the â¬100 billion that it was offered to rescue Bankia and other troubled banks in June 2012.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Luis de Guindos, Spainâs economy minister, said Monday that the results showed that âthe stigma of Spanish banks has disappeared.â In terms of Spainâs overall economy, which came out of recession in late 2013 and has since outperformed most other European economies, âthere is no recovery without a solvent banking sector,â he said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Luis MarÃ­a Linde, the governor of Spainâs central bank, noted during a news conference on Sunday that Spanish banks had taken almost â¬280 billion in charges from 2008 to June 2014, to increase provisions against bad loans made to a property sector whose bubble burst in 2008, shortly after the start of the financial crisis.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Linde said the results showed the restructuring efforts had âyielded fruitâ and forecast that Spanish banks âface the future with healthy balance sheets and solid solvency positions.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Banco Santander and BBVA, the two Spanish banks that have led the sector&#8217;s international expansion, were among the best performers in the central bank tests, showing generous capital cushions under the review&#8217;s most adverse economic crisis situation. Santander had a capital ratio of 8.9 percent and BBVA a level of 9 percent, well above the European Central Bank&#8217;s threshold of 5.5 percent needed to withstand a severe downturn, according to the review.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Spanish results contrasted with those of <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/10/26/italian-banks-are-the-weakest-performers-in-e-c-b-tests/">Italian banks</a>, which have come under pressure during the European debt crisis but avoided the kind of international rescue needed to salvage savings banks in Spain.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Nine of the 15 Italian lenders examined by the European Central Bank had capital shortfalls at the end of 2013 and four of them must still raise more capital, including <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2013/02/23/business/global/the-patron-of-siena-monte-dei-paschi-stumbles.html">Monte dei Paschi di Siena</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Robert Tornabell, a professor of banking at the Esade business school in Barcelona, said that âthese are excellent results, especially if compared with those of Italy.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He added: âSpanish taxpayers will continue to pay for Bankia and the bailout that we needed, but there has really also been a very important cleaning up of the balance sheetâ in the Spanish banking sector.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Portuguese banks also had mixed results, only months after <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/08/04/business/international/banco-espirito-santo-of-portugal-appears-headed-for-a-bailout.html">the rescue</a> of one of the countryâs largest lenders, Banco EspÃ­rito Santo, which was sunk by bad loans made to other companies in the EspÃ­rito Santo family empire.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Millennium BCP, Portugal&#8217;s largest listed bank, failed to meet the requirements set by the European Central Bank but said Sunday that it had since taken sufficient steps to avoid having to raise more capital or sell major assets.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe capital shortfall identified has already been covered,â it said in a statement released Sunday evening.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The banking crisis in Spain mostly affected the savings banks, or cajas, that led reckless property lending during the construction boom, in part under the pressure of politicians who sat on their boards.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The number of cajas in Spain has shrunk to just a handful today from 45 before the 2008 crisis, after several rounds of consolidation. Among the most recent transactions, BBVA agreed in July to pay <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/22/spain-sells-catalunya-banc-to-bbva-for-1-6-billion">â¬1.2 billion for Catalunya Banc</a>, one of the bailed-out cajas that had, itself, been formed by merging three smaller banks in the Spanish region of Catalonia.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Bankia has arguably been <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/01/15/business/international/bailed-out-bankia-is-symbol-of-spains-financial-revival.htm">Exhibit A in Spainâs banking turnaround</a>, even as its former management team remains under investigation over its handling of an initial public offering and the bank faces accusations that its directors made personal purchases totaling about â¬15 million using unaccounted corporate credit cards.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Bankia, which was the result of a seven-way merger of savings banks, needed just over half of the â¬41 billion European bailout to stay afloat, after being nationalized in May 2012. It returned to profit in 2013, after cutting staff and selling assets, and has since continued to post strong earnings.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Last week, Bankia reported that third-quarter profit had risen 65 percent, to â¬266 million, from the year-earlier period.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Spanish government is hoping to fully divest its controlling stake in Bankia, but has not set a timetable to do so.</p>
